  "What did Einstein propose about light to explain the photoelectric effect?": "",
  "Light is made of continuous waves with unlimited energy": "",
  "Light travels faster in metal than in a vacuum": "",
  "Light consists of quantized packets of energy called photons": "",
  "Light can only be absorbed by metals at high temperatures": "",
  "Einstein proposed that light consists of discrete energy packets called photons, each with energy E = hf. This quantum model explained why only light above a certain frequency can eject electrons, regardless of intensity.": "",
  "What is a photon?": "",
  "A negatively charged particle that orbits the atomic nucleus": "",
  "A quantum of electromagnetic energy with energy E = hf": "",
  "A neutral particle found inside the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "A wave that carries sound energy through a solid medium": "",
  "A photon is a discrete packet (quantum) of electromagnetic energy. Its energy depends on frequency according to E = hf, where h is Planck's constant and f is the frequency of the light.": "",
  "Define the term 'threshold frequency' in the context of the photoelectric effect.": "",
  "The highest frequency of light a metal can reflect without damage": "",
  "The frequency at which light intensity reaches its maximum value": "",
  "The minimum frequency of light needed to eject electrons from a metal": "",
  "The frequency at which photoelectrons reach the speed of light": "",
  "The threshold frequency (f₀) is the minimum frequency of incident light required to eject electrons from a particular metal surface. Below this frequency, no electrons are emitted regardless of light intensity.": "",
  "What is a photoelectron?": "",
  "An electron that emits visible light when it moves through a wire": "",
  "An electron that has been ejected from a surface by incident light": "",
  "A photon that has been converted into an electron inside a prism": "",
  "An electron bound tightly within the innermost shell of an atom": "",
  "A photoelectron is an electron that has been emitted from a material's surface after absorbing energy from incident light (a photon). The term distinguishes electrons freed by the photoelectric effect from electrons in other contexts.": "",
  "What does the term 'quantized' mean in physics?": "",
  "Existing only in discrete, specific amounts rather than any value": "",
  "Moving at a constant speed without any acceleration at all": "",
  "Being too small to measure with any available instruments": "",
  "Traveling in a straight line without bending or diffracting": "",
  "Quantized means that a physical quantity can only take on specific discrete values, not a continuous range. Energy in the photoelectric effect is quantized — photons carry energy in fixed amounts E = hf rather than arbitrary values.": "",
  "What is the stopping potential in a photoelectric experiment?": "",
  "The voltage needed to accelerate photoelectrons to maximum speed": "",
  "The minimum voltage needed to reduce the photoelectric current to zero": "",
  "The voltage at which the light source turns off automatically": "",
  "The voltage needed to heat the metal above threshold temperature": "",
  "The stopping potential (V₀) is the minimum reverse voltage needed to stop the most energetic photoelectrons, reducing the current to zero. It relates to maximum kinetic energy by KE_max = eV₀.": "",
  "Define the term 'intensity' of light as used in photoelectric experiments.": "",
  "The color of the light as perceived by the human eye": "",
  "The speed at which light travels through a given medium": "",
  "The energy delivered per unit area per unit time by the light": "",
  "The wavelength of the light measured in nanometers": "",
  "Light intensity is the power (energy per unit time) delivered per unit area. In the photon model, higher intensity means more photons hitting the surface each second, which increases the number of ejected electrons but not their individual energy.": "",
  "What does the term 'electron volt' (eV) refer to?": "",
  "The voltage produced by a single electron in a circuit": "",
  "The speed of an electron moving through a vacuum tube": "",
  "The energy gained by an electron accelerated through one volt": "",
  "The charge carried by one mole of electrons in solution": "",
  "An electron volt (eV) is a unit of energy equal to the energy gained by a single electron when it is accelerated through a potential difference of one volt. It equals 1.60 × 10⁻¹⁹ joules and is commonly used in atomic and particle physics.": "",
  "What is meant by the 'wave-particle duality' of light?": "",
  "Light can only behave as a wave during diffraction experiments": "",
  "Light exhibits both wave-like and particle-like behavior": "",
  "Light is always a particle and never exhibits wave properties": "",
  "Light switches permanently from a wave to a particle at high energy": "",
  "Wave-particle duality means that light can behave as a wave (showing interference and diffraction) and also as a particle (as shown by the photoelectric effect, where individual photons eject individual electrons). Neither model alone fully describes all behaviors of light.": "",
  "What is the relationship between a photon's energy and its wavelength?": "",
  "Photon energy is directly proportional to wavelength": "",
  "Photon energy is inversely proportional to wavelength": "",
  "Photon energy is independent of wavelength entirely": "",
  "Photon energy equals wavelength times Planck's constant": "",
  "Since E = hf and f = c/λ, we get E = hc/λ. This shows that photon energy is inversely proportional to wavelength — shorter wavelength light (like UV) has higher energy photons than longer wavelength light (like red).": "",
  "Define 'photocurrent' in a photoelectric experiment.": "",
  "The current produced by a battery that powers the light source": "",
  "The electric current formed by the flow of ejected photoelectrons": "",
  "The maximum voltage measured across a photoelectric cell": "",
  "The resistance of the metal plate to incoming photons of light": "",
  "Photocurrent is the electric current that results from the flow of photoelectrons ejected from a metal surface by incident light. Its magnitude depends on the intensity of the light (number of photons) and increases with greater intensity above the threshold frequency.": "",
  "A student shines ultraviolet light on a zinc plate and observes electrons being ejected. When she switches to red light of the same intensity, no electrons are emitted. What best explains this observation?": "",
  "Red light has a higher frequency than ultraviolet light": "",
  "Red light photons have less energy than the work function of zinc": "",
  "Red light is absorbed by the air before reaching the zinc plate": "",
  "The zinc plate can only interact with one specific color of light": "",
  "Red light has a lower frequency (and therefore lower photon energy) than ultraviolet light. If the photon energy of red light is below zinc's work function, no individual photon has enough energy to eject an electron, regardless of intensity.": "",
  "In a lab, a student doubles the intensity of light shining on a metal surface while keeping the frequency constant and above threshold. What happens to the maximum kinetic energy and the number of photoelectrons?": "",
  "Both the maximum KE and the number of photoelectrons double": "",
  "The maximum KE stays the same and the number of photoelectrons doubles": "",
  "The maximum KE doubles and the number of photoelectrons stays the same": "",
  "Neither the maximum KE nor the number of photoelectrons changes": "",
  "Doubling the intensity means twice as many photons hit the surface per second, so the number of ejected electrons doubles. However, the maximum KE of each electron depends only on the frequency of the photons (KE_max = hf − φ), which has not changed.": "",
  "A researcher measures the stopping potential for a metal and finds it is 1.5 V when illuminated with light of a certain frequency. If the light frequency is increased, what happens to the stopping potential?": "",
  "The stopping potential decreases because higher frequency means less energy": "",
  "The stopping potential remains 1.5 V regardless of the frequency used": "",
  "The stopping potential increases because each photon gives more energy to electrons": "",
  "The stopping potential drops to zero because frequency and voltage are unrelated": "",
  "Higher frequency photons carry more energy (E = hf). Since the work function is constant for a given metal, the extra energy goes into the kinetic energy of the ejected electrons (KE_max = hf − φ). A greater maximum KE requires a larger stopping potential to halt the electrons.": "",
  "A student notices that green light ejects electrons from metal A but not from metal B. Which conclusion is most supported by this observation?": "",
  "Metal B is thicker than metal A so the light cannot penetrate it": "",
  "Metal B has a higher work function than metal A": "",
  "Metal A reflects green light while metal B absorbs it completely": "",
  "Metal B has fewer electrons available on its surface than metal A": "",
  "Since the same green light ejects electrons from metal A but not from metal B, the photon energy exceeds metal A's work function but falls below metal B's work function. This means metal B has a higher work function (more energy is needed to free its surface electrons).": "",
  "In a photoelectric experiment, a scientist graphs maximum KE of photoelectrons versus frequency of incident light. What does the slope of this straight line represent?": "",
